@NODE "introduction" "WAVRepair - Introduction"

WAVRepair - Introduction

WAVRepair is a simple tool for repairing WAV files with corrupt or damaged headers. My girlfriend is a professional musician and regularly uses a portable recording device to record performances as WAV files on a memory card. Occasionally, this device would fail to write the correct header to the file, resulting in a WAV file that contained all the recorded sound data but could not be opened by most software.

To get around this I initially rebuilt the header manually with a hex editor, but when it happened again I decided to write a small CLI tool to automate it. I then heard that some of her colleagues had had similar experience with different makes and models of recording devices, and so I knew it wasn't simply a quirk of her particular device. So I decided to make a proper GUI version... And this is it!

WAVRepair can highlight the issues it finds in the header of any WAV file, and can repair many issues directly in place. Additionally, it will also highlight any parameters which aren't strictly part of the specification but which don't cause any problems. Another possibility is to write a totally new file with a new header and the data from the old, damaged file.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "disclaimer" "WAVRepair - Disclaimer"

WAVRepair - Disclaimer

While I have tried to ensure this software won't cause any harm to anyone's system or data, I can't guarantee it, and I can't be held responsible for any loss or damage caused by the use of this software. There are so many different computer configurations out there, and I only have a couple of combinations that I can test, so all I can say is, "It Works on My Machine" :)

Since WAVRepair can directly edit your recordings or other WAV files, please make a backup copy first!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "operation" "WAVRepair - What It Does"

WAVRepair - What It Does

WAVRepair works by reading the file header of the WAV file chosen, and comparing this to calculated values based on the WAV specification. Parameters which are completely wrong will normally cause the file to play incorrectly in most software, or sometimes not at all.

These issues can be caused by a number of things, such as poorly implemented creation or editing software, corrupted file due to a computer issue, or a problem with the recording device in the first place. Problems like this will be highlighted as errors and in most cases can be repaired in-place by WAVRepair.

Some issues are quite minor and are simply caused by creation or editing software bending the rules a little bit in order to store extra information within the file. Such issues will be highlighted by WAVRepair as warnings, and they usually won't be repaired in-place as to do so might destroy information which might otherwise be useful. In most cases these files will still play fine in nearly all software as the critical parameters are correct.

WAVRepair can also be used to copy the audio data to a brand new file, complete with a brand new, standard header. Such files will lose any additional information hidden in the headers, but will be 100% compliant with the WAV specification.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "requirements" "WAVRepair - Requirements"

WAVRepair Requirements

WAVRepair has some minimum requirements which you should really have sorted out before running the application...

 - MUI 3.8
 - AmigaOS 3.x 

WAVRepair has been tested on OS4.1, OS3.9 and MorphOS 3.3.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "installation" "WAVRepair - Installation"

Installing WAVRepair

Installing WAVRepair requires nothing special. Just copy the entire drawer to wherever you want it and run it from there.

A separate OS4 icon has been included in the archive. If you would like to use it, copy it to the main WAVRepair location. Thanks to Tim Cranley for the icon!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "usage" "WAVRepair - Usage"

Using WAVRepair

WAVRepair can simply be run by double-clicking on its icon. It can also be started from the shell with the optional parameter of a filename which will be the file chosen when the main window opens.

@{b}The Main Window@{ub}
The main window initially presents a number of information fields, along with a file selection gadget at the top of the window, and a status bar and three buttons at the bottom of the window.
Initially only the most commonly corrupted and critical data fields are shown, but a "Show Additional Details" check box allows the user to show additional data fields from the file header.

To read about what each of the data fields means, see the @{"advanced information" Link "advanced"} section.

To use WAVRepair, start by selecting the file you would like to examine with the gadget at the top of the window. Once the file is entered in the text gadget, click the "Examine" button at the bottom of the screen. WAVRepair will read the contents of the header and populate all the data fields with the relevant information.

At this point, the labels of the fields will be highlighted based on their status.
Values highlighted in green show that the parameter matches the expected value.
Values highlighted in orange are warnings, so the parameter doesn't match the expected value but the file should still be ok. Normally these warnings are due to custom information being inserted in between the standard chunks of data resulting in an unexpected chunk size.
Values highlighted in red are errors, and will more than likely mean the file does not play properly, or not at all. These parameters are the ones that WAVRepair will attempt to repair when the "Repair" option is used.

A summary of the examination will be shown in the status line at the bottom of the window. If desired, the file can now be repaired or the data copied to a new file by clicking on the respective buttons.

@{b}Repair@{ub}
This option will attempt to replace the parameters that were flagged as warnings (highlighted in red) with the expected values, directly in the chosen file. @{b}Note:@{ub} This will directly modify the original file selected, so please make sure you have a backup!
The Repair option should simply fix the file, and clicking on "Examine" again once done will re-examine the file, hopefully showing no more errors. Warnings will not be repaired themselves with this method as they should not cause any problems for playing the file, and might remove some otherwise useful information.

@{b}Save to New File@{ub}
This option will present a file requester where you can choose a new file to save the audio data to. This file will be created with a brand new header which matches the data from the original file, and just the actual audio data chunk will be copied from the original file. Any extra information hidden between chunks will be lost, however this isn't part of the audio so it should be ok. The resulting file should be 100% compliant with the WAV format, and should therefore work in any software.
For large files this can take some time, but the status bar at the bottom of the window will show you the copying progress.

Some functions can also be accessed from the @{"window's menus" LINK "menus"}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "menus" "WAVRepair - Menus"

WAVRepair Menus

WAVRepair's main window provides some standard menus accessible with the right mouse button. These give access to some of WAVRepair's standard functions, and also provide keyboard shortcuts. These menus are as follows:

- Project
   - About WAVRepair... (RAmiga-?): Opens the About requester showing version information.
   - Help... (RAmiga-H): Opens this guide file.
   - Quit (RAmiga-Q): Quits WAVRepair.
- Tools
   - Examine (RAmiga-E): Examines the selected file.
   - Repair... (RAmiga-R): Repairs the selected file in place.
   - Save to New File... (RAmiga-S): Saves audio data to a new file with new headers.

More information on these functions can be read in the @{"Usage section" LINK "usage"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "configuration" "WAVRepair - Configuration"

Configuring WAVRepair

There is currently only one option for configuring WAVRepair, stored as a Tooltype in the WAVRepair icon. It is used to set the size of the copy buffer used when copying a file's data to a new file, and is set as follows:

COPYBUFFERSIZE=<bytes>

By default this setting is 65536 bytes (64KB), which should be fine in most cases. However, if you have some spare RAM and you deal with large WAV files, setting this value larger can help to speed up the copying process. Values of 4MB can make copying a 600MB file about 20% faster than the default, for example. Setting the buffer size much smaller than 64KB will slow things down a lot...

@ENDNODE
@NODE "limitations" "WAVRepair - Limitations and Bugs"

WAVRepair - Limitations and Bugs

@{b}Limitations@{ub}

There are a few limitations that you should be aware of before using WAVRepair:

 - Only works with little-endian data. Don't worry, this is the standard used on all platforms so it will work with files from Macs, PCs, PPC Macs, Amigas, portable devices... WAV files stored in big-endian format are very rare and have a different header so will simply be rejected by WAVRepair.

 - Only PCM data is supported. While other audio formats could in theory be stored in a WAV file, I've never seen one so this shouldn't be an issue. If you get an error on the "Audio Format ID" field, this could be either corruption, or due to the audio not being in PCM format, so be careful here.

 - WAVRepair is @{b}untested@{ub} with files larger than 2GB. It @{i}should@{ui} work, but just make sure you have a backup! Also, it will not work with files over 4GB, but neither the standard nor most filesystems support files that size so this should never be a problem.

 - If the header is badly damaged, there are some parameters WAVRepair will not be able to figure out for itself. In these cases it may or may not be able to repair the file, or may write incorrect values back to the header, resulting in a more damaged file. Again, make sure you have a backup!

 - Only one data chunk is supported. If more than one data chunk is included in the file, it will be ignored for repair, and not copied over to a new file. Files with multiple chunks are very rare, but if you need this function, please @{"let me know" Link "aboutme"} and I might add support.

@{b}Known bugs@{ub}

 - On OS3.x / MUI 3.8, if the additional information fields are hidden when the file is examined, and later shown, the highlighting of fields does not work. Clicking "Examine" again when the fields are shown will show the highlighting as normal.

If you think you've found a bug in WAVRepair, please @{"let me know!" Link "aboutme"} Or, if you find a WAV file that WAVRepair can't repair, let me know as well and I'll see what I can do.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "advanced" "WAVRepair - Advanced"

WAVRepair - Advanced Information

WAV files generally have a standard structure consisting of an overall chunk and at least two sub-chunks of information. Each chunk and sub-chunk starts with a 4-byte ID, followed by a 4-byte long integer containing the size of that chunk.
The first sub-chunk is the "Format" chunk, and it describes the file format used for the data sub-chunk, and this format chunk is generally where the problems lie.
The second sub-chunk is the "Data" chunk, and it holds the corresponding audio data.

WAVRepair recognises all the standard parameters normally found in the header of a WAV file. A description of these parameters can be found below.

 - Chunk Size (32-bit integer)
This the the complete size of all the sub-chunks the main chunk contains. Normally this is simply the sizes of the data and format sub-chunks added together, but occasionally also includes extra bytes not belonging to any sub-chunk.

 - Subchunk 1 Size (32-bit integer)
This is the size of the Format chunk, and is normally 16 bytes. These 16 bytes are rigidly described in the WAV standard, but for audio formats other than PCM it can be larger. These other formats are beyond the scope of WAVRepair's capabilities and so will show up a bunch of errors. Probably, anyway, since I've never seen such a file in the wild...

 - Subchunk 2 Size (32-bit integer)
This is the size of the Data chunk (and hence the amount of audio information), and should normally be the (file size - subchunk 1 size - chunk header), but again this can differ based on whether additional data has been added outside the normal sub-chunks.

 - File size (32-bit integer)
Should be the size of the format and data sub-chunks plus the header main chunk header, but again can differ based on extra information being added outside the normal sub-chunks.

 - File Format ID (4 bytes)
This indicates the format of the main chunk, and should always be "WAVE".

 - Audio Format ID (16-bit integer)
This should normally be 1 for PCM data. Other values mean other data formats, perhaps compressed, and are beyond the normal WAV spec and WAVRepair's capabilities to understand.

 - Number of Channels (16-bit integer)
This is the number of independent audio streams, and is normally 1 for mono or 2 for stereo, but can be any number of channels in theory.

 - Sample Rate (32-bit integer)
This is the number of samples per second. Normally 44,100 for CD quality audio, but often one of the other standard frequencies and can be anything.

 - Byte Rate (32-bit integer)
This is the number of bytes per second used for the audio stream, so should be the sample rate times channels times bytes per sample.

 - Block Align (16-bit integer)
This is the number of bytes needed for a single sample, so the data chunk should always be a multiple of this number of bytes in size. It should be number of bytes per sample times channels.

 - Bits/Sample (16-bit integer)
This is the number of bits per sample and per channel, and describes the normal resolution of the audio. Usually 8 or 16 bits (1 or 2 bytes), but can be any multiple of 8.

More information on the WAV format can be found in the Microsoft Developer Network documentation, or a good visualisation can be found at https://ccrma.stanford.edu/courses/422/projects/WaveFormat/

@ENDNODE
